# AI Pre-Shipment Risk Decision Agent

This project is a demo prototype for an internal AI competition.

Goal:
Build a runnable demo that helps inspect actual system information, compare with tracking sheet, check known issues, and generate shipment recommendation.

Current focus:
- inspect input Excel files
- build minimal parser
- generate first runnable prototype

## Version 1 structure

- `input_data/`: real PM / AE Excel reference files
- `demo_cases/`: fake GO / Conditional Go / No-Go scenario files
- `output/`: generated JSON reports
- `pre_shipment/xlsx_reader.py`: dependency-free `.xlsx` reader
- `pre_shipment/parser.py`: sheet inspection and field extraction
- `pre_shipment/demo_case_parser.py`: lightweight parser for fake demo scenarios
- `pre_shipment/decision.py`: simple mismatch and risk rules
- `pre_shipment/html_report.py`: human-readable HTML overview and detail pages
- `pre_shipment/mapping.py`: sheet hints and field aliases
- `demo.py`: runnable end-to-end prototype

## Field mapping plan

Expected configuration:
- source sheet: usually `MS1 Schedule`
- fields: `project_name`, `system_level`, `cpu_board`, `hardware_items`, `firmware_versions`

Actual system / firmware information:
- source sheet: usually `MS4_sysinfo_*`
- fields: `product_name`, `product_part_number`, `board_part_number`, `product_version`, `firmware_versions`, `bmc_ip_address`, `bmc_mac_address`

Known issues:
- source sheet: usually `Known issue`
- fields: `item`, `type`, `description`, `status`, `level`, `resolution`, `target_date`

## Current workbook observations

- `AE_ES_Tracking_FWA-3080.xlsx`
  - `MS1 Schedule` looks like expected configuration and planned firmware versions
  - `MS4_sysinfo_ESE0425246` looks like actual firmware / FRU / LAN information
  - `Known issue` is the project known issue list
- `PM_ES_Tracking_SKY-721E3.xlsx`
  - `MS1 Schedule` looks like expected configuration
  - there is no clear actual sysinfo sheet in this workbook
  - there is no clear known issue sheet in this workbook

The PM and AE files appear to be for different projects, so version 1 analyzes each workbook independently instead of forcing them into a single shipment record.

## Run

```powershell
python demo.py
```

The script prints a summary and writes JSON reports into `output/`.

It also generates HTML reports for demo use:
- `output/html/index.html`: overview page
- `output/html/*.html`: one detail page per workbook

## Demo cases

The project now supports two input styles in the same run:
- real Excel workbooks under `input_data/`
- fake scenario files under `demo_cases/`

Each fake demo case uses:
- `*_expected_config.csv`
- `*_actual_sysinfo.txt`
- `*_known_issues.csv`

The current fake scenarios are designed to show:
- `GO`
- `Conditional Go`
- `No-Go`
